ðŸ“œ 1. Add .Events(events => events.Edit("onEditRbParts")) inside your .Editable()
csharp
Copy
Edit
.Editable(editable => editable.Mode(GridEditMode.InCell).Enabled(true))
.Events(events => events.Edit("onEditRbParts"))
(Note: You already have .Events inside your DataSource â€” this one goes inside .Editable() or Grid level events.)

ðŸ“œ 2. Add this JavaScript function:
javascript
Copy
Edit
function onEditRbParts(e) {
    var grid = $("#RbPartsMaterialDetailsRebuiltPartsGrid").data("kendoGrid");

    if (!e.model.isNew()) {  // Not a new row => Disable fields

        if (e.container.find("[name='RebuiltStockNum']").length) {
            var rebuiltField = e.container.find("[name='RebuiltStockNum']");
            rebuiltField.prop("disabled", true).addClass("field-disabled"); // Disable and add CSS
        }

        if (e.container.find("[name='MmsStockCode']").length) {
            var mmsField = e.container.find("[name='MmsStockCode']");
            mmsField.prop("disabled", true).addClass("field-disabled"); // Disable and add CSS
        }
    }
}
ðŸ“œ 3. Add the CSS to make disabled fields look nice:
html
Copy
Edit
<style>
/* Style for disabled fields */
.field-disabled {
    background-color: #eeeeee !important; /* Light gray */
    color: #555555 !important;             /* Slightly faded text */
    border: 1px solid #cccccc !important;   /* Soft border */
    pointer-events: none;                   /* No mouse interaction */
}

/* Remove hover and focus effects */
.field-disabled:hover,
.field-disabled:focus,
.field-disabled:active {
    background-color: #eeeeee !important;
    color: #555555 !important;
    border: 1px solid #cccccc !important;
    box-shadow: none !important;
}
</style>
